{"/service/ndnp/mimtptc/batch_mimtptc_dexter_ver01/data/42047197/00340588678/1946060101/0424.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE 8\nl CITIZENS P.\nv 4 av\u00ab I**\nLocal 862 UAW-CIO, joined in a PAO drive to back up OPA during Derby Day in Lou\nisville, Kentucky. The sign shown above marks the scene where more than 10,000 post cards\nwere written to Washington backing the campaign for Price Control.\nUAW-CIO Plan Speeds Up\nUnemployment Benefits\nThose liours-long line-ups in\nfront ol* the Unemployment\nOffices in the Detroit Metropol\nitan area are n thing: of the\npast with the installation of a\nnow system of self-registration.\nClayton Johnson, UAW-CIO Un\nemployment Compensation Direc\ntor, after more than a year\u2019s cam\npaigning. saw his plan for elimi\nnating these tiresome line-ups go\nm\\to effect for a trial period, and if\nwarranted, the plan will be ex\npanded to cover the entire Michi\ngan area.\nInstead of servicing on an aver\nage of ten persons per hour, clerks\nIn the unemployment offices can\nnow service at least 30 persons\nwithout any extra work on their\npart.\nThe claimant simply lines up.\nreceives what is known as Form\nUC-700 and his appointment date,\ntakes the form home. There he\ntills out the papers, returns on the\nscheduled date, the clerk checks\nthe papers and countersigns.\nAID FOB CLAIMANTS\nUntil now everyone who applied\nfor benetits stood in line while the\nclerks tilled In his name, address,\nnumber of dependents, etc., etc.\nIf the claimant experiences any\nditticulty tilling out the forms he\nmay have anyone in his household\nor his local union aid him.\nIn a letter to all UAW Locals In\nDetroit area, Johnson outlined\ntlie self-registration idea and en\nclosed sample copies. He asked\nunion presidents to provide help to\nclaimants who might experience\ndifficulty in tilling out the papers.\nThis, he said, would help the de\npartment give unemployment In\nsurance claimants the speediest\npossible service.\nThe UAW Unemployment Com\npensation Department wishes to ad\nvise all regions that they stand\nready and willing to assist them in\nsolving any problems of policy in\ntheir respective states.\nWrite UAW-CIO Unemployment\nDepartment, 2525 Barium Tower,\nDetroit 26, Michigan.\nThe UAW has eliminated differ\nential rates based on sex and estab\nlished an industrial Bill of Rights.\nDollars for Democracy\nUncle Sam\nPraises CIO\nBond Record\nWASHINGTON \u2014CTO mem\nbers have bought about $5 bil\nlion worth of war bonds and\n\u201cemployes in industries in\nwhich the CIO has strong or\nganization had the best record\nof any group in the country,\u201d\nthe U. S. Treasury Department\nlast week informed CTO Presi\ndent Philip Murray.\nIt was the first estimate from\nthe Treasury on union bond pur\nchases and although the $5 billion\nwas cited as a \"rough\u2019' figure,\nMurray was told that \"It means\nthat CIO members bought about\none-eighth of the total of E Bonds\nsold to the American public.\"\nThe ClO\u2019s outstanding contri\nbution to the War Bond drive was\ndisclosed in a letter to Murray\nfrom Joe Swire, associate chief of\nthe Treasury's CIO Labor Section.\nSwire told the CIO president:\nONE-EIGHTH OF TOTAL\n\"I have checked as carefully as\npossible into the figures and esti\nmate that purchases of War Bonds\nby members of the CIO from May,\n1941, through December, 1945, is\nroughly about $5 billion. This is a\nrough but conservative estimate.\u2019\u2019\nDentist Extracts\n$310,486 from GM\nST. LOUlS \u2014General Motors must\npay Elmer G. Kesling, Stoddard,\nMo., dentist, $310,486 for Infringing\non his patent for a vacuum booster\ndevice, the U. S. District Court\nhere has ruled.\nGM used the vacuum booster\nmechanism on the gear shift of\nChevrolet cars.\nThe court based its award on a\nrate of 12 cents for each of the\n2,034,400 times that GM used the\ngadget on its gear shifts.\nUNITED AUTOMOBILE WORKER\nPact Signed\nat Acme\nLocal 716 UAW-CIO. (Acme\nAluminum Alloy) foundry work\ners have recently signed a union\nshop contract, with provisions for\ndues check-off, improved griev\nance procedure, and a vacation\npolicy as follows.\nOne year of service, one week\npaid vacation for 40 hours; 800\nhours service, 20 hours pay. Two\nto five years service, 60 hours pay,\nand five years and over, 80 hours\npay. A returning World War II\nveteran shall be granted vacation\npay on the same basis as If he had\nbeen working in the plant.\nOn Nov. 19, 1945 the UAW ne\ngotiated a 10 cent increase, and a\nmeeting is scheduled with the\ncompany on May 24, for a 9 cent\nincrease retroactive until Novem\nber 19, 1945.\n$15,100 Reward for Capture of\nThugs Attacking Briggs Workers\nA total of $15,100 in rewards is\noffered by the UAW-CIO Interna\ntional union and local unions for\ninformation leading to the arrest\nand conviction of persons respon\nsible for the brutal beating of four\nmembers of Briggs Local 212 dur\ning the past 14 months.\nMost recent victim of the beat\nings was Ken Morris, recording\nsecretary of the local and editor of\nits official publication. \"The Voice\nof Local 212.\"\nMorris, a World War II veteran\nwho spent 47 months in the armed\nforces, was seized and beaten\nseverely after he had parked his\ncar behind his home the evening of\nMay 31. He sustained a fractured\nskull, jaw, arm and leg.\nGRAND JURY PROBE\nAt the request of UAW-CIO\nPresident Walter Reuther, Region\nal Director Emil Mazey and Pres.\nTom Clampitt of Local 212, a De\ntroit grand jury Is investigating\nthe series of beatings. These offi\ncers described the beatings as a\n\"systematic campaign of terror\nagainst officers and well-known\nmembers of Briggs Local 212.\"\nDuring a fourteen month period\nfour members of the local union\nhave been the victims of five dif\nferent beatings.\nThe rewards offered are as fol\nlows: SIO,OOO, .International union;\n$5,000, Briggs Local 212; SIOO,\nBudd Local 306.\nPROFESSIONAL JOB\nThe assault on Morris was of\nthe same pattern as those of the\nthree other victims. In each case\ntwo men did the beating with lead\npipes. It was a professional, scien\ntific, methodical, unemotional job.\nThere was no indication by the\nattackers of the reason for the\nassault, no threats that It would\nPackard Local 190 Okays\nNew Improved Agreement\nPackard Local 190, UAW-CIO,\nhas ratified a new agreement pro\nviding for an 18 H cent wage In\ncrease, retroactive to March 4, an\nimproved union security clause\nbased on a dues check-off and\nnumerous other improvements In\nworking conditions.\nNorman Matthews, Co-Director\nof Region 1, UAW-CIO, stated that\nthe new agreement represented a\nsubstantial victory for the Packard\nworkers.\n\"We made a major step forward\nin winning the dues check-off,\nwhich will provide Local 190 with\na high decree of union security,\"\nMatthews said. \"In addition, we\nsecured a 1 good shift preference\nclause, based on seniority, plus an\nanti-discrimination clause and\nmore than 90 days of retroactive\npay. Together with other refine\nments in the agreement, these\ngains will solidify and strengthen\nthe UAW-CIO in the Packard\nplant.\"\n$3,500,000 ANNUALLY\nA spokesman for Packard man\nagement announced that the 18 H\ncents wage increase for hourly-rat\ned workers would add up to\n$3,500,000 more per year in wages\nfor the Packard workers.\nSmoking privileges are provided\nin a clause \u2019which permits smoking\nUAW Gives\nPAC $20,000\nThe UAW-CIO International\nExecutive Bpard voted at its Cleve\nland meeting to contribute $20,000\nto the National CIO-PAC.\nThis contribution matches that\nof the United Steelworkers, the\nAmalgamated Clothing Workers\nand other large CIO unions.\nThe funds will be used to as\nsist in the election of progressive\nand pro-labor candidates in the\n1946 elections.\nhappen again if the victim did not\nmeet certain conditions, no swear\ning or imprecations. In fact the\nthugs who did the beatings did not\nspeak at all.\nEvery evidence indicates that\nthe beatings were administered by\npeople outside the union, probably\nmembers of anti-labor groups or,\nmore likely, professional hirelings\nof anti-labor groups.\n\"We believe that these inci\ndents, which seem to comprise a\npattern of deliberate terror\nagainst union members and offi\ncers, demand a complete and\nthorough investigation and the\napprehension and conviction of\nthe perpetrators, no matter who\nthey are or whose interests they\nserve,\" the union officials said.\nThe first victim, in March, 1945,\nwas Art Vega, well known member\nof Local 212 and a candidate for\npresident of the local in the 1945\nunion elections. Vega is also a\nWorld War II veteran.\nRoy Snowden, Local 212 ser-\nKEN MORRIS after brutal beating\naMfIMM r\non all jobs any time, except in\ndesignated fire hazard areas.\nThe shift preference clausa pro\nvides standard premiums of 5 per\ncent for 2nd shift workers, and 7tt\nper cent for 3rd shift workers,\nand choice of shifts is governed\nstrictly by seniority, within de\npartments.\nA unique feature of the leave of\nabsence provision permits veterans\nto obtain leaves for the purpose of\nenjoying 'educational benefits un\nder the GI Bill of Rights.\nSeamen Get\nIIAW Support\nFull support to the CIO Mari\ntime Unions, in their struggle to\nachieve wage gains comparable to\nincreases in other industries plus\nimproved working conditions, was\nvoted by the UAW-CIO Interna\ntional Exednive Board at its June\n4 and 5 meeting in Cleveland, Ohio.\nThe Maritime workers are nego\ntiating in Washington for the fol\nlowing demands:\nForty-hour week as against\n56-hour week.\nWage increases of 22 cents to\n85 cents per hour, according to\njob ratings.\nOvertime payment for all work\nin excess of eight hours per day,\nfrom $1.25 to $1.75, according to\njob ratings.\nSettlement of wage demands,\nretroactive to October 1, 1945.\nPersonnel for ail job ratings to\nbe hired through the Union Hall.\nThe Board resolution was critical\nof President Truman\u2019s threat to\nuse federal power to break a Mari\ntime workers\u2019 strike, in the event\nsuch a strike is called on June 15.\nIt called on local unions to send\nwires and letters of support to\nWashington, pledging support to\nthe Maritime workers.\ngeant-at-arms, for the last several\nyears, was beaten on two occasions\n\u2014in May and September, 1945.\nWOMAN BEATEN\nMrs. Genora Dollinger, a Local\n212 steward, and her husband, Sol\nDollinger, a member of Budd Local\n306, were beaten last October by\ntwo men who broke Into their\nhome during the night.\nMorris, who was discharged\nfrom the U. S. Army last Decem\nber, was elected recording secre\ntary of the local union in February\nwithout opposition. The post of\neditor of the union paper has tra\nditionally been an assignment of\nthe recording secretary in Local\n212. Morris had held both posts\nbefore his entrance into the Army,\nhaving resigned from them when\nhe enlisted in 1941.\nOn an average day, 7,000,000\npeople are so sick or disabled that\nthey cannot go to work or carry\non their usual activities.\nJune, 1946","height":"25314","width":"17472"}}
